    formationText: "Virtue is the opposite of being ruled by our impulses. It is a firm, settled disposition to do good, formed by repeated good choices until the good becomes second nature. Like a muscle, virtue grows with practice. The Church speaks of human virtues such as prudence, justice, courage, and self-control, and of the higher gifts of faith, hope, and love that God pours into us by grace.\n\nThis matters for daily life. We are not stuck with our worst tendencies. With God's grace and steady effort, we can be reshaped, becoming more patient, more honest, more generous. Growth in virtue is how the love we receive from God becomes visible in the kind of person we are slowly becoming.",
