    day: 146,
    title: "Why Do Catholics Believe the Eucharist Is Really Jesus?",
    category: "The Mass and Eucharist",
    summary: "We believe it because Jesus said it plainly, the apostles handed it on, and the Church has held it from the start.",
    formationText: "In John chapter 6, Jesus says, I am the bread of life, and then, more startlingly, my flesh is true food and my blood is true drink. When many listeners were shocked and said this teaching was hard, Jesus did not soften it or explain it away as a symbol. He let some walk away rather than take back his words, because he meant them. At the Last Supper he made it concrete: this is my body, this is my blood.\n\nSaint Paul, writing to the Corinthians, warns that whoever eats the bread or drinks the cup unworthily sins against the Body and Blood of the Lord, language that makes no sense if it were only a symbol. From the earliest centuries, Christians believed and worshipped the Eucharist as truly Jesus. The Catholic Church believes it because Christ said it, the apostles handed it on, and the Church has faithfully held it ever since. We take Jesus at his word and let wonder grow.",
    reflection: "When you hear Jesus say my flesh is true food, can you let yourself take him simply at his word?",
